    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-12-07T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-12-07T04:00:00-05:00" n="810"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d810">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002/793: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-12-07T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 7, 1938—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 7—3:07 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1465. The British Ambassador informs me that as it is clear that unless the
                    pressure for the employment of Japanese in the <pb facs="0754" n="750"
                        xml:id="pg_750"/> Chinese Maritime Customs ceases or the recruiting of
                    foreigners is resumed on an international basis the balance of the service will
                    be seriously affected, he has now been instructed to invite the Chinese
                    Government to agree in principle to resumption of the recruiting of the foreign
                    staff for the customs on a broad basis. In this connection see my despatch No.
                    1809 of November 9th as well as my despatch No. 1813 November 15th<note n="24"
                        xml:id="d810fn24">Neither printed.</note> which should reach the Department
                    in the near future.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Chungking and Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
